Neutral value for all FreeU options b1, b2, s1 and s2 is 1. Not unexpected, but as they are not the default values in the node, I mention it here.

b1: responsible for the larger areas on the image
b2: responsible for the smaller areas on the image
s1: responsible for the details in b2
s2: responsible for the details in b1

So s1 belongs to b2 and s1 to b2. The numbers 1 and 2 are misleading.

b1 and b2 with a value lower than 1 causes artefacts, like missing last sample steps (noisy image).

Every value over 1 increases overall contrast and saturation of colors but with emphasis of their area of responsibility.

If you think of an upper body portrait with a blurry background:

b1: background, even skin
b2: clothes, bigger areas of hair, eye brows, eyes, nose, mouth
s1: tiniest details, like hair on the skin, iris, finest skin structure, fabric fibers
s2: small details like skin and clothes structure

Increasing...
...b1 increases contrast and causes lost of small details, but tiny details don't get lost
...b2 increases contrast and causes lost of tiny details, but small details don't get lost
...s1 increases contrast and tiny details
...s1 increases contrast and small details

Decreasing...
...b1 causes artefacts (lower than 1)
...b2 causes artefacts (lower than 1)
...s1 causes lost of tiny details without losing contrast (dreamy look)
...s2 causes lost of small details without losing contrast (elegant, still realtic beauty look)
